viation and new frontiers for capitalist accumulation. Using the Girl Effect, the philanthropic brand of Nike, Inc., as a central case study, the book examines how these corporations seek to address the problems of gendered poverty and inequality, yet do so using an instrumental logic that shifts the burden of development onto girls and women without transforming the structural conditions that produce poverty. These practices, in turn, enable corporations to expand their legitimacy, authority, and reach while sidestepping contradictions in their business practices that often exacerbate conditions of vulnerability for girls and women. With a keen eye towards justice, author Kathryn Moeller concludes that these corporatized development practices de-politicize girls’ and women’s demands for fair labor practices and a just global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCorporate imagexManagement. 0aCorporationsxCharitable contributionsvCase studies. 0aPoor girlsxServices forzDeveloping countries. 0aYoung womenxServices forzDeveloping countries. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  abusiness and economics.  acontemporary politics.  aeconomics.  aending poverty.  afair labor practices for women.  agender studies.  agender.  agendered poverty.  agirl effect nike.  agirl effect.  aglobal economy.  aglobal south.  ahistorical rise of girl effect.  anew capitalist frontiers.  anike in global south.  anike.  apoor women in global south.  asocial justice.  asocial science.  athird world women.  awomen in business.  awomen in the global south.  awomens issues.  awomens labor issues.  awomens studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052028639940uhttps://ww